00:36:49,458 --> 00:36:52,461
Not hard on the eyes,
as my mother would say.

500
00:36:54,838 --> 00:36:58,175
- Did he ever make a pass at you?
- No.

501
00:36:59,343 --> 00:37:02,638
No, Dr. Sheehan's a good doctor,
he would never...

502
00:37:06,016 --> 00:37:08,310
Could I have a glass of water, please?

503
00:37:08,394 --> 00:37:09,812
No problem.

504
00:37:24,660 --> 00:37:26,995
- Thank you, Marshal.
- Sure.

505
00:37:30,707 --> 00:37:34,086
I just have one more question for you,
Mrs. Kearns.

506
00:37:37,339 --> 00:37:40,634
Did you ever meet a patient
named Andrew Laeddis?

507
00:37:43,720 --> 00:37:44,888
No.

508
00:37:46,265 --> 00:37:48,100
Never heard of him.

509
00:37:53,856 --> 00:37:55,023
<i>She was coached.</i>

510
00:37:55,607 --> 00:37:58,193
She used practically the same words
as Cawley and the nurse,

511
00:37:58,277 --> 00:37:59,778
like she'd been told exactly what to say.

512
00:37:59,862 --> 00:38:01,697
Who's Andrew Laeddis?

513
00:38:06,285 --> 00:38:10,622
You asked every one of those patients
back there about him. Who is he?

514
00:38:14,460 --> 00:38:17,921
What the hell, boss?
I'm your partner, for Christ's sake.

515
00:38:18,005 --> 00:38:19,882
We just met, Chuck.

516
00:38:20,299 --> 00:38:23,886
You've been on the beat for a long time.
You've got a duty. You've got a career.

517
00:38:23,969 --> 00:38:28,390
What I'm doing,
it's not exactly by the book.

518
00:38:29,808 --> 00:38:32,603
I don't give a damn
about by-the-book, boss.

519
00:38:32,686 --> 00:38:35,564
I just wanna know
what the hell's going on.

520
00:38:39,818 --> 00:38:42,446
When this case came over the wires,

521
00:38:43,322 --> 00:38:46,325
I requested it specifically,
you understand?

522
00:38:46,742 --> 00:38:47,951
Why?

523
00:38:50,204 --> 00:38:51,914
Andrew Laeddis,

524
00:38:52,748 --> 00:38:54,917
he was the maintenance man
in the apartment building

525
00:38:55,000 --> 00:38:57,169
where my wife and I lived.

526
00:38:58,212 --> 00:38:59,463
Okay.

527
00:39:01,298 --> 00:39:03,342
He was also a firebug.

528
00:39:06,136 --> 00:39:08,764
Andrew Laeddis lit the match

529
00:39:11,517 --> 00:39:14,436
that caused the fire that killed my wife.

530
00:39:22,653 --> 00:39:24,112
Let them out!

531
00:39:26,782 --> 00:39:30,118
- What happened to Laeddis?
- He got away with it.

532
00:39:30,202 --> 00:39:32,621
Laeddis got away with it
and then he disappeared.

533
00:39:32,704 --> 00:39:35,707
About a year ago, I open up the paper
and there he is.

534
00:39:35,791 --> 00:39:40,295
Ugly-looking son of a bitch. Huge scar
from his right temple down to his left lip.

535
00:39:40,379 --> 00:39:43,840
Eyes different colors.
Not the type of face you'd forget.

536
00:39:43,924 --> 00:39:47,052
He burned down a schoolhouse,
killed two people,

537
00:39:47,135 --> 00:39:48,887
said voices told him to do it.

538
00:39:48,971 --> 00:39:51,598
First he went to prison,
then he got transferred here.

539
00:39:51,682 --> 00:39:53,892
- Then what?
- Then nothing.

540
00:39:53,976 --> 00:39:57,729
He vanished like he never existed.
No record whatsoever.

541
00:39:57,813 --> 00:40:00,190
Pretty sure he's not in Ward B.
That leaves Ward C.

542
00:40:00,274 --> 00:40:01,567
Or he could be dead.

543
00:40:01,650 --> 00:40:04,236
So could Rachel Solando,
for that matter.

544
00:40:04,319 --> 00:40:06,905
Lot of places to hide a body here.

545
00:40:07,698 --> 00:40:10,617
Only one place
no one would really notice.

546
00:40:22,170 --> 00:40:26,258
That patient, Bridget Kearns,
when she sent me for water,

547
00:40:26,341 --> 00:40:29,261
she said something to you back there,
didn't she?

548
00:40:29,344 --> 00:40:30,470
No.

549
00:40:32,389 --> 00:40:33,682
Come on, boss.

550
00:40:37,561 --> 00:40:39,104
She wrote it.

551
00:40:54,536 --> 00:40:55,704
Boss!

552
00:40:56,038 --> 00:40:59,625
We gotta get indoors. It's turning
into a fucking Kansas out here.

553
00:40:59,708 --> 00:41:01,960
- Hold on.
- No, let's go!

554
00:41:04,838 --> 00:41:06,298
Watch out!

555
00:41:08,383 --> 00:41:09,635
Jesus!

556
00:41:11,386 --> 00:41:13,680
- Come on! Up there!
- Let's go!

557
00:41:16,350 --> 00:41:18,310
Get in there! Let's go!

558
00:41:21,938 --> 00:41:23,148
Boss!

559
00:41:30,238 --> 00:41:32,282
- God!
- Jesus Christ!

560
00:41:33,617 --> 00:41:35,577
Damn it. God!

561
00:41:44,252 --> 00:41:47,547
- You okay, boss?
- Yeah, I'm all right.

562
00:41:54,554 --> 00:41:58,809
So if Laeddis is here,
what are you gonna do about it?

563
00:42:01,853 --> 00:42:04,147
I'm not here to kill Laeddis.

564
00:42:11,822 --> 00:42:13,573
If it was my wife, I'd kill him.

565
00:42:13,657 --> 00:42:14,658
Twice.

566
00:42:25,419 --> 00:42:30,048
<i>When we got through the gates
at Dachau, the SS guards surrendered.</i>

567
00:42:38,640 --> 00:42:44,312
The <i>Kommandant</i> tried to kill himself
before we got there, but he...

568
00:42:45,480 --> 00:42:46,773
<i>He botched it.</i>

569
00:42:48,316 --> 00:42:50,318
Took him an hour to die.

570
00:42:55,490 --> 00:42:59,161
When I went outside,
I saw all the bodies on the ground.

571
00:43:03,623 --> 00:43:05,333
<i>Too many to count.</i>

572
00:43:32,027 --> 00:43:33,862
Too many to imagine.

573
00:43:36,490 --> 00:43:38,200
So, yeah, the...

574
00:43:40,368 --> 00:43:42,287
The guards surrendered,
we took their guns,

575
00:43:42,370 --> 00:43:44,289
<i>and we lined them up.</i>

576
00:44:28,500 --> 00:44:30,627
It wasn't warfare. It was...

577
00:44:32,671 --> 00:44:34,172
It was murder.

578
00:44:37,676 --> 00:44:40,595
Yeah, I've had enough of killing.

579
00:44:43,098 --> 00:44:45,100
That's not why I'm here.

580
00:44:46,142 --> 00:44:48,186
So what is this all about?

581
00:44:50,230 --> 00:44:56,111
After Laeddis vanished, I started doing
some checking on Ashecliffe.

582
00:44:57,612 --> 00:45:00,699
A lot of people know about this place,
but no one wants to talk.

583
00:45:00,782 --> 00:45:04,744
You know, it's like it...
It's like they're scared or something.

584
00:45:06,788 --> 00:45:09,875
You know, this place is funded
by a special grant

585
00:45:10,792 --> 00:45:13,628
from The House
Un-American Activities Committee?

586
00:45:13,712 --> 00:45:16,882
HUAC? And how exactly
are we fighting the communists

587
00:45:16,965 --> 00:45:19,301
from an island in Boston Harbor?

588
00:45:19,926 --> 00:45:22,554
By conducting experiments on the mind.

589
00:45:23,972 --> 00:45:25,432
At least that's my guess.

590
00:45:25,515 --> 00:45:27,225
And you think that's going on here?

591
00:45:27,309 --> 00:45:29,811
Like I said, no one would talk, right?

592
00:45:29,895 --> 00:45:32,564
Till I found somebody
who used to be a patient here.

593
00:45:32,647 --> 00:45:37,027
Guy's name is George Noyce.
Nice college kid. Socialist.

594
00:45:37,110 --> 00:45:39,154
He gets offered some money
to do a psych study.

595
00:45:39,237 --> 00:45:40,614
Guess what they were testing?

596
00:45:40,697 --> 00:45:41,781
Toothpaste.

597
00:45:41,865 --> 00:45:44,242
So, he starts
seeing dragons everywhere.

598
00:45:44,326 --> 00:45:49,331
He almost beats his professor to death.
Ends up here in Ashecliffe, Ward C.

599
00:45:49,998 --> 00:45:53,460
They release him after one year, right?
And what does he do?

600
00:45:53,543 --> 00:45:58,465
Two weeks on the mainland, he walks
into a bar, stabs three men to death.

601
00:45:59,257 --> 00:46:03,970
His lawyer pleads insanity, but Noyce,
he stands up in the courtroom and he...

602
00:46:04,054 --> 00:46:08,516
He begs the judge for the electric chair.
Anywhere but a mental hospital.

603
00:46:09,142 --> 00:46:11,728
Judge gives him life in Dedham Prison.

604
00:46:12,771 --> 00:46:13,813
And you found him.

605
00:46:13,897 --> 00:46:15,565
Yeah, I found him.

606
00:46:15,649 --> 00:46:18,151
Well, he's a mess.

607
00:46:19,736 --> 00:46:21,863
But it's pretty clear
from what he tells me.

608
00:46:21,947 --> 00:46:23,073
What?

609
00:46:23,156 --> 00:46:25,909
They're experimenting on people here.

610
00:46:25,992 --> 00:46:27,702
I don't know, boss.

611
00:46:28,995 --> 00:46:30,497
How do you believe a crazy guy?

612
00:46:30,580 --> 00:46:32,248
That's the beauty of it, isn't it?

613
00:46:32,332 --> 00:46:36,586
Crazy people, they're the perfect
subjects. They talk, nobody listens.

614
00:46:37,170 --> 00:46:38,838
I stood at Dachau.

615
00:46:39,089 --> 00:46:43,760
We saw what human beings are
capable of doing to each other, right?

616
00:46:43,843 --> 00:46:46,429
For Christ's sakes, we fought
a goddamn war to stop them,

617
00:46:46,513 --> 00:46:50,266
and now... Now I find out it may be
happening here? On our soil?

618
00:46:50,350 --> 00:46:51,393
No.

619
00:46:52,560 --> 00:46:55,188
So what are you really here to do, Ted?

620
00:46:55,897 --> 00:46:59,693
I'm gonna get the proof,
I'm gonna go back,

621
00:46:59,776 --> 00:47:03,446
and I'm gonna blow the lid off this place.
That's it.

622
00:47:04,864 --> 00:47:06,366
Wait a minute.

623
00:47:06,950 --> 00:47:09,744
You started asking around
about Ashecliffe,

624
00:47:09,828 --> 00:47:11,246
waiting for a chance to get out here,

625
00:47:11,329 --> 00:47:13,915
and then suddenly
they need a U.S. Marshal?

626
00:47:13,999 --> 00:47:17,877
Yeah, I got lucky. There was a patient
escape. It was the perfect excuse.

627
00:47:17,961 --> 00:47:20,964
No, no, no, boss.
Luck doesn't work that way.

628
00:47:21,047 --> 00:47:22,716
The world doesn't work that way.

629
00:47:22,799 --> 00:47:26,094
They got an electrified fence
around a septic facility.

630
00:47:26,177 --> 00:47:29,305
Ward C is inside a Civil War fort?

631
00:47:29,389 --> 00:47:33,059
A Chief of Staff with ties to the OSS?
Funding from HUAC?

632
00:47:33,143 --> 00:47:37,731
I mean, Jesus Christ, everything about
this place stinks of government ops.

633
00:47:37,814 --> 00:47:39,190
What if they wanted you here?

634
00:47:39,274 --> 00:47:41,151
- Bullshit.
- You were asking questions.

635
00:47:41,234 --> 00:47:42,277
- Bullshit! Bullshit!
- Bullshit.

636
00:47:42,360 --> 00:47:43,611
We came here for Rachel Solando.

637
00:47:43,695 --> 00:47:46,573
Where's one shred of evidence
she even existed?

638
00:47:46,656 --> 00:47:47,824
There's no way they could've known

639
00:47:47,907 --> 00:47:49,284
I'd be assigned to this case.
There's no way.

640
00:47:49,367 --> 00:47:52,704
What if while you were looking into
them, they were looking into you?

641
00:47:52,787 --> 00:47:55,999
All they had to do was fake an escape
to get you here, and now they have you.

642
00:47:56,082 --> 00:47:57,876
Now they have us both. Here! Now!

643
00:48:02,130 --> 00:48:06,468
<i>Marshals, are you out here?
This is Deputy Warden McPherson.</i>

644
00:48:07,594 --> 00:48:08,636
<i>Marshals!</i>

645
00:48:08,720 --> 00:48:10,722
How about that? They found us, huh?

646
00:48:10,805 --> 00:48:13,308
It's an island, boss.
They're always gonna find us.

647
00:48:14,684 --> 00:48:16,311
<i>I know you're in there.</i>

648
00:48:17,896 --> 00:48:21,399
We're getting off this goddamn island.
You and me. Come on.

649
00:48:25,779 --> 00:48:27,489
- Come on!
- Go, go!

650
00:48:37,290 --> 00:48:40,418
Get dried off.
Dr. Cawley wants to talk to you now.

651
00:48:41,044 --> 00:48:44,589
And hurry up! This thing is turning
into a goddamn hurricane!

652
00:48:49,761 --> 00:48:53,681
I dropped those suits off to be cleaned.
Should be ready by tomorrow.

653
00:48:54,182 --> 00:48:56,976
That is, if we all don't wash away first.

654
00:48:57,060 --> 00:49:01,523
You know, speaking of which, I'm afraid
your smokes are pretty much done for.

655
00:49:02,107 --> 00:49:03,274
So...

656
00:49:04,943 --> 00:49:07,070
This is our only choice, huh?

657
00:49:07,153 --> 00:49:10,198
Got something really nice in
a prison gray if that don't work for you.

658
00:49:10,281 --> 00:49:13,201
Now that you mention it,
these are just fine.

659
00:49:13,910 --> 00:49:15,537
That's why I must repeat my insistence

660
00:49:15,620 --> 00:49:18,748
that all Ward C patients
be placed in manual restraints.

661
00:49:19,415 --> 00:49:22,752
If the facility floods, they'll drown.
You know that.

662
00:49:23,211 --> 00:49:24,462
That would take a lot of flooding.

663
00:49:24,546 --> 00:49:27,215
We're on an island in the middle
of the ocean during a hurricane.

664
00:49:27,298 --> 00:49:29,968
A lot of flooding seems like
a distinct possibility.

665
00:49:30,051 --> 00:49:32,387
It's a gamble, Stephen.
Say the power fails.

666
00:49:32,470 --> 00:49:33,721
There's a backup generator.

667
00:49:33,805 --> 00:49:36,516
And if that goes,
the cell doors will open.

668
00:49:38,059 --> 00:49:39,727
Where are they going to go?

669
00:49:40,395 --> 00:49:43,398
They can't just hop a ferry, scoot over
to the mainland and wreak havoc.

670
00:49:43,481 --> 00:49:44,482
Oh, you're quite right.

671
00:49:44,566 --> 00:49:47,735
They're far more likely
to wreak havoc right here on us.

672
00:49:48,653 --> 00:49:51,573
If they're manacled to the floor,
they'll die.

673
00:49:51,906 --> 00:49:53,783
This is 24 human beings.

674
00:49:54,409 --> 00:49:55,743
And you can live with that, can you?

675
00:49:55,910 --> 00:49:57,912
Well, frankly, if it were up to me,

676
00:49:57,996 --> 00:50:01,332
I'd put all 42 in Wards A and B
in manual restraints as well.

677
00:50:01,416 --> 00:50:04,294
- Excuse me! Excuse me.
- Marshal.

678
00:50:04,377 --> 00:50:06,921
I'm sorry, Doctor.
I just have one quick question.

679
00:50:07,005 --> 00:50:08,214
Yes, I'll be with you in a moment.

680
00:50:08,298 --> 00:50:11,301
When we spoke this morning
about Rachel Solando's note...

681
00:50:11,384 --> 00:50:13,094
"The law of four." I love that.

682
00:50:13,178 --> 00:50:16,723
...you said you had no idea what that
second line could refer to, correct?

683
00:50:17,891 --> 00:50:22,228
"Who is 67?" Yes, I'm afraid I still don't.
None of us do.

684
00:50:23,646 --> 00:50:24,898
Nothing comes to mind?

685
00:50:27,609 --> 00:50:28,818
Nothing?

686
00:50:32,780 --> 00:50:37,827
Because I believe I just heard you say
there are 24 patients in Ward C

687
00:50:37,911 --> 00:50:40,371
and 42 patients in Wards A and B,

688
00:50:40,455 --> 00:50:43,917
which means there's a total of,
what, 66 patients at this facility?

689
00:50:45,585 --> 00:50:46,586
That is correct, yes.

690
00:50:50,048 --> 00:50:53,134
Well, it seems to me
Rachel Solando was suggesting

691
00:50:53,218 --> 00:50:56,346
that you have a 67th patient, Doctor.

692
00:50:57,931 --> 00:50:59,432
But I'm afraid we don't.

693
00:50:59,974 --> 00:51:01,893
This is ridiculous.
What are they doing here?

694
00:51:01,976 --> 00:51:04,145
We're doing our goddamn job.

695
00:51:04,479 --> 00:51:07,148
Didn't McPherson tell you
the good news?

696
00:51:08,316 --> 00:51:10,735
No. What's the good news, Doctor?

697
00:51:10,818 --> 00:51:12,570
Rachel's been found.

698
00:51:13,613 --> 00:51:14,989
She's here.

699
00:51:16,157 --> 00:51:17,659
Safe and sound.

700
00:51:29,337 --> 00:51:31,381
There's not a mark on her.

701
00:51:35,009 --> 00:51:36,427
Who are these men?

702
00:51:39,806 --> 00:51:41,391
Why are they in my house?

703
00:51:41,474 --> 00:51:45,979
Police officers, Rachel.
They have a few questions.

704
00:51:49,524 --> 00:51:50,692
Ma'am.

705
00:51:54,070 --> 00:51:58,658
There has been a sighting of a known
communist subversive in this area,

706
00:51:58,741 --> 00:52:00,660
passing out literature.

707
00:52:02,453 --> 00:52:03,663
Here?

708
00:52:05,873 --> 00:52:07,500
In this neighborhood?

709
00:52:07,583 --> 00:52:09,335
Yes, I'm afraid so.

710
00:52:10,712 --> 00:52:14,299
Now if you could tell us what you did
yesterday, where you were,

711
00:52:14,382 --> 00:52:16,509
it would really help us
narrow down our search.

712
00:52:18,177 --> 00:52:19,387
Yes...

713
00:52:22,140 --> 00:52:23,474
Well, I...

714
00:52:26,394 --> 00:52:29,230
I made breakfast
for Jim and the children,

715
00:52:30,898 --> 00:52:32,317
and then I

716
00:52:34,193 --> 00:52:36,404
packed Jim's lunch and he left.

717
00:52:40,074 --> 00:52:42,744
Then I sent the children off to school.

718
00:52:47,165 --> 00:52:48,416
And then

719
00:52:54,839 --> 00:52:57,884
I decided to take a long swim
in the lake.

720
00:53:04,766 --> 00:53:05,975
I see.

721
00:53:09,687 --> 00:53:11,230
And after that?

722
00:53:19,405 --> 00:53:20,740
After that,

723
00:53:30,541 --> 00:53:32,168
I thought of you.

724
00:53:38,174 --> 00:53:42,136
I'm sorry, ma'am,
I don't know what you're talking about.

725
00:53:45,139 --> 00:53:48,101
Don't you know how lonely
I've been, Jim?

726
00:53:54,065 --> 00:53:55,149
You're gone.

727
00:53:59,404 --> 00:54:00,863
You're dead.

728
00:54:05,910 --> 00:54:07,787
I cry every night.

729
00:54:13,793 --> 00:54:16,003
How am I supposed to survive?

730
00:54:17,505 --> 00:54:18,673
God.

731
00:54:29,058 --> 00:54:32,353
Rachel, it'll be all right.

732
00:54:35,606 --> 00:54:37,650
I'm so sorry, but every...

733
00:54:39,360 --> 00:54:42,196
Everything's gonna be all right. Okay?

734
00:54:44,115 --> 00:54:45,575
I buried you.

735
00:54:47,910 --> 00:54:50,538
I buried an empty casket.
Your body rained down,

736
00:54:50,621 --> 00:54:54,125
lumps of flesh splashing into the sea,
eaten by sharks.

737
00:54:58,379 --> 00:55:01,007
My Jim's dead,
so who the fuck are you?

738
00:55:04,427 --> 00:55:06,095
Who the fuck are you?

739
00:55:06,846 --> 00:55:07,972
- Who are you?
- Hey, hey, hey, hey.

740
00:55:08,055 --> 00:55:09,640
- Who are you?
- It's okay. Rachel. Rachel, it's all right.

741
00:55:09,724 --> 00:55:12,226
Let me go! No!

742
00:55:13,895 --> 00:55:16,022
- Rachel, it's okay.
